      "writtenOn": "2026-04-14T02:36:43Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e They could and not would. They necessarily don\u0027t have to.\n\nDoesn\u0027t change my point.  It\u0027s one model device.\n\n\u003e per Modbus spec to connect to device.\n\nPer the MODBUS spec, not per the DeltaECD70000020PMM spec.  Type\u003d DeltaECD70000020PMM should mean all the device specific details are assumed and set to defaults for that device so that by default, you can connect to the most common implementation of that device.  See the difference?  These aren\u0027t meant to house per-device specifics.  If the device can truly support all these parameters and all these enumerations, ok.  But certainly it doesn\u0027t support every possible register in the modbus spec, it implements a subset.  That should be owned by the backend.\n\n\u003e The way you are creating analogy none of the i2c bus numbers, i2c addresses, min/max readings, thresholds, Units, polling rate, etc, should have ever been modeled in EM.\n\nBus numbers, change per device.  I2c addresses change per device.  min/max readings change per device, thresholds change per device.  Units are only implemented for external sensor where they\u0027re not known, polling rate has intelligent defaults and isn\u0027t required to be specified most times.  We didn\u0027t specify i2c register number, which is a way we COULD\u0027VE implemented TMP75 devices, but you want the implementation to own the backend and pick good defaults.\n\n\u003e Why that should go in code? \n\nBecause that lets people keep them common between implementations.  \"modbus device\" isn\u0027t a thing, just like there\u0027s no type called \"i2c device\"\n\n\n\u003e Its per device and will vary from vendor to vendor for what they choose.\n\nEXACTLY, but for a given device, it\u0027s fixed, so it goes in the backend and gets exposed by type.  THis means that we can separate out code such that I (the EM maintainer) don\u0027t have to review individual registers maps for correctness.",
      "parentUuid": "4ff48450_e965a077",
      "revId": "e5bdf248b1acfda6f3ed93e2c3732a0a151c68dd",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
